changed how open orders at Kraken are fetched and parsed

before: code parsed a description string.
problem: special order types, such as "take profit limit" or "stop loss
  limit" caused NumberFormatExceptions because the format of the
  description string differed.
  
solution: Kraken API delivers all relevant information about an order
  nicely split up as a JSON object, in addition to the description
  string. So, just take the data from the JSON object.

not so nice yet: Special order types do not match to a LimitOrder, so
  we ignore them for now.

Defined the getOrderResult function for getting information about a
completed order. This is an MtGox-specific api, and there is currently
no generic XChange mechanism to access this information across
exchanges. This commit does not add the generic access. However, if the
generic support will be added in the future, it is very likely to be
using the function from this commit anyway.
Until, this function can be used in MtGox-specific way, like MtGoxLag.

e.g., consider https://novaexchange.com/remote/v2/market/info/BTC_LTC/.

BTC. As a result, the market name should be target_base.

Add space before "%" percentage sign

In German, the rule is to have a space before the percentage sign.

Reference a: http://www.duden.de/rechtschreibung/Prozent `Beispiel: 5 Prozent oder 5 %`
Reference b: http://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prozentzeichen `Wie bei Maßeinheiten wird zwischen die Zahl und das Prozentzeichen ein geschütztes Leerzeichen gesetzt (siehe Schreibweise von Zahlen).[7] Der Duden empfiehlt hier, einen kleineren, festen Zwischenraum zu verwenden.[8]`

Even better would be to use a non breaking space but that would break a lot of views, so I changed it to a simple space here.

Add temporary matchers for the irregular key names of Rails 4.0.0

Rails 4.0.0 introduced the following new keys:
  - errors.messages.restrict_dependent_destroy.one
  - errors.messages.restrict_dependent_destroy.many
  - activemodel.errors.messages.restrict_dependent_destroy.one
  - activemodel.errors.messages.restrict_dependent_destroy.many
  - activerecord.errors.messages.restrict_dependent_destroy.one
  - activerecord.errors.messages.restrict_dependent_destroy.many

These key names are irregular from the point of view of i18n-spec.
It interpretes them as pluralization keys, but they aren't.

The new matchers treats them specially and can avoid false positives.

Clarify errors.messages.too_(long|short)

Previous messages literally read too_long: "is too long (not more than X characters)", too_short: "is too short (not less than X characters)" which IMO was confusing as it could be read as "is too short (i.e., is not less than…)" whereas the actual meaning is "is too short (it *should* not be less than…)".

The version I suggest translates to "is too long (more than X characters)" and "is too short (less than X characters)" respectively which is unambiguous. It can now be read as a natural sentence "Attribute IS too short (less than…)" without the user having to assume another verb for the details given in the parentheses.

This reverts commit e6a1c4f1b081b193f45a7f011039f7e55779127e.

This commit broke the meaning of "distance_of_time_in_words". That
method is supposed to return the description of a time interval
without specifying if it's in the future or in the past. That is,
it should return "about 1 hour" instead of "about 1 hour ago" or
"in about 1 hour from now".

Well, this commit replaced "about 1 hour" with "1 hour ago", which is
wrong. You can't now use the "distance_of_time_in_words" method to
describe dates in the future, because the final result would be
something like "in about 2 hours ago from now".

Fixes to Norwegian Bokmal locale (nb)

First of all, Norwegian uses ',' as a separator, not '.'. Thus, in
Norwegian you would write '3,2' not '3.2' as you do in English.

Secondly, in Norwegian both ' ' and '.' can be used as delimiter,
however, ' ' is primarily used.

Thirdly, according to the SI system the kilo- prefix has a lowercase k,
not uppercase K.

Use less technical language on error templates.

The geeky sounding: "Konnte dieses {{model}} Objekt nicht speichern"
seems to use 'Object' to circumvent the problem that the gender of
the model isn't known, but needed to adapt 'diese'.

I've just dropped 'dieses' which sounds linguistically similar bad
but much less geeky. And it allows nice errors when adding human
translations for {{model}}: "Konnte {{model}} nicht speichern: 1 Fehler."

Fixing number translations for i18n

Actualy there's a problem with number_to_currency which throws the following
error:

  can't convert String into Hash

This is because in es-MX.yml currency is formatted as:

  currency:
    format: "%u%n"
    delimiter: ","
    unit: "$"
    precision: 2
    separator: "."

Where it should be:

  currency:
    format:
      format: "%u%n"
      delimiter: ","
      unit: "$"
      precision: 2
      separator: "."

Also removed some configuration concurrency leaving the same precision and
delimiter as defualt for all cases:

es-MX:
  number:
    currency:
      format:
        format: "%u%n"
        unit: "$"
    format:
      delimiter: ","
      precision: 2
      separator: "."
    human:
      storage_units:
        format: "%n %u"
        units:
          byte:
            one:   "Byte"
            other: "Bytes"
          kb: "KB"
          mb: "MB"
          gb: "GB"
          tb: "TB"

Also there was a bug with the storage units that with this configuration is
fixed.

Some simple tests:

  = number_to_currency(1_000_345.55)
  => $1,000,345.55
  = number_to_percentage(99.50)
  => 99.50%
  = number_with_delimiter(1_000_345.55)
  => 1,000,345.55
  = number_with_precision(1_000_345.55)
  => 1,000,345.55
  = number_to_human_size(1_234_567)
  => 1.18 MB

Support closing stream (#877)

* Support closing stream

In this version, we can close stream as following:

```ruby
client = Twitter::Streaming::Client.new do |config|
  # Set up configuration
end

t = Thread.new do
  client.filter(track: keyword) do |object|
    # process object
  end
end

Signal.trap(:TERM) do
  # terminate process silently
  client.close
  exit true
end
```

Use addressable for building query string (#758)

As URI component of Ruby standard library only conform RFC3986 and
it doesn't encode '*' character and that leads to errors. It seems Addressable
library conforms RFC3986, RFC3987 and RFC6570 and it encodes '*' character
as well.

Following test case will be failed in the current version and it returns
'Twitter::Error::Unauthorized' exception.

require 'twitter'

client = Twitter::Streaming::Client.new do |config|
  config.consumer_key        = 'YOUR_CONSUMER_KEY'
  config.consumer_secret     = 'YOUR_CONSUMER_SECRET'
  config.access_token        = 'YOUR_ACCESS_TOKEN'
  config.access_token_secret = 'YOUR_ACCESS_SECRET'
end

filter_params = {
  :track => '(*^0^*)',
  :language => 'es'
}
client.filter(filter_params) do |object|
  puts object.text if object.is_a?(Twitter::Tweet)
end

Chomp empty URL fragments from the end of websites

This fixes a nasty bug that occurred when a URL fragment in a Twitter
user's website is present but empty (e.g. "http://example.com#"). In
this case, the @normalized_fragment instance variable in an
Addressable::URI object is set every time the normalized_fragment method
is invoked, setting the instance variable, thus violating the object's
frozen state.

Namespace registered Faraday middleware

Just namespacing the code for a middleware in a module is, sadly, not
enough, as the name when you register it might clash with middleware
from other libraries that register the same type of middleware (for
example, the [Diffbot ruby client][1] registers a `:parse_json`
middleware, which provokes projects using both the twitter and diffbot
gems to raise an error when an error response comes back from twitter.

[1]: https://github.com/diffbot/diffbot-ruby-client

Dont allow unacceptable IO objects in update_with_media

We ran into a bug where a 401 error was returned for any File-like
object that didn't have a to_io method defined
(ActionPack::HttpUploadedFile in this case).

Since the contract of this object is to have a to_io method otherwise
it will be included in the oauth signature (cause of 401) then we should
short circuit early on when we know this is supposed to be a File like
object. Later on we aren't sure exactly when we include/exclude params
from the signature.

Add Twitter::Error::RequestTimeout

This is a new class to catch timeout errors, such that they may be
retried.

It may be used as follows:

begin
  # Make a request using a Twitter::REST::Client
rescue Twitter::Error::RequestTimeout
  retry
end

Prior to this patch, to get the same behavior, you'd need to do this:

begin
  # Make a request using a Twitter::REST::Client
rescue Timeout::Error, Twitter::Error => error
  if error.is_a?(Timeout::Error) || error.cause.is_a?(Timeout::Error) || error.cause.is_a?(Faraday::Error::TimeoutError)
    retry
  else
    raise
  end
end

Use method_defined? instead of responds_to?

The string extension for "camelize" checks if this method has already been defined by called responds_to?. This, however, doesn't work because it's being called on the String class rather than an instance of the String class (and hence, will always return false).

This means that if String#camelize is already defined, it will always be overridden. One notable situation where this breaks things is when you call something like 'some_string'.camelize(:lower) since the ActiveSupport version of camelize can accept an optional argument whereas the one defined in the Twitter gem cannot.

add another sort type: "dot separated numbers"

This matches IP addresses, version numbers, etc.

1. Take input string and run split('.').
2. Loop through returned array:
    a) Is a == b? Yes, skip to next number. No, goto next comparison.
    b) Is a < b?  Yes, return that b is greater.
    c) Is a > b?  Yes, return that a is greater.

Say we run sortDotSep("192.168.1.56", "192.168.1.59"):
    192 == 192 # next number
    168 == 168 # next number
      1 == 1   # next number
     56 <  59  # return that number b is bigger

Or, say we run sortDotSep("192.168.1.56", "192.128.1.59"):
    192 == 192 # next number
    168 >  128 # return that number a is bigger

Changelog v0.3.10
Tag all logged messages through Makara's logger with `[Makara]`

Handle edge cases when storing staged data and deleting expired entries

Freeze time when starting the request and use always that time to check
whether some entry has expired, instead of considering it expired at any
point during the request. Also, use always the max TTL seen for any
staged or stored entry.
Improve some copy, fix typos and do some style related changes
Show a warning when trying to set `Makara::Cache.store`

Replace ":" and "|" in custom proxy ids and warn about it

These characters are used as separators in the context cookie.

Support sticking manually to master without persisting

That is, Proxy#stick_to_master!(false) should stick the proxy to master
for the current request but not beyond that. We shouldn't store that in
the cookie for future requests.

Use a "staging" area in context to avoid TTL from starting within request

That is, when we stick a proxy to master in a request and the request is
very long, if we set the expiration time based on the TTL right at the
moment of sticking, we might unstick before the request even ends. This
is probably not the intention, so instead of setting the expiration time
right when the proxy is stuck, we wait until the context is committed,
and at that time we move the newly stuck proxies to the storage area
from the staging area.
Amend a few other references to config when it should be proxy

Move fetching and storing context to middleware

Now context doesn't know anything about cookies, only about the hash
with the data.
Write unit tests for `Makara::Cookie`

Set `expires` option as well as `max-age`

This ensures support on old IE versions, while for other browsers it'll
be simply ignored in favour of `max-age`.

Extract parsing and storing cookie to its own module

And while there, increase the buffer for cookie's max-age to 5 seconds
instead of 1. It shouldn't harm, and it can be easily overridden.

Stop referring to the proxy id as "config id", it's very confusing

The id defined in the configuration for a proxy was being referred as
`config_id` in several places, so I had kept it, but it was certainly
confusing, it wasn't easy to know what I was talking about. That id
really identifies the proxy, so there is no point on using a misleading
name for it.
Make Pool#next implementation clearer
Update `README` with some details and fixes after review
Change cookie identifier to not interferre with previous set ones
Set default context always, even if `init` is not invoked
Reorder and reindent a bit to match style
Don't hardcode cookie identifier in tests
Update README with respect to context as query param
Remove unnecessary test assertion about proxy's master context
Modify Makara middleware to simply init and commit new context
Implement a way to release all stuck connections or a given config

Simplify Proxy, we don't really need to track whether we stuck in the request

It's enough with being stuck until the cache expires or all connections
are released (which will be added later). Releasing all connections no
longer depends on a specific context, so all we need to rely on is the
cache.

Adapt Proxy to use new Makara::Context

We don't need to track any context hashes anymore, just whether we are
currently stuck in this request or not.

Remove context from connection pool management

It's always set to the current context when the pool is intialised, and
then compared against the current context as well. The only case in
which it could be relevant is when the context is forced to be a new one
manually, in the middle of a request. This will be handled in a
different way.
Clear expired stuck configurations from the cookie

Remove everything related to Makara's cache

We'll rely exclusively on cookie store for the context.

Support configurable context cookie options

These were handled directly by the middleware before, but now that
cookie setting is done in Context, support for this should be moved
here.
Update spec helper and write tests for new Context behaviour

Convert Context into a stickiness state representation

Instead of keeping track of two MD5 hashes that allow us to be stuck to
master for 1 or 2 requests at most, keep whether we are currently stuck
or not, for each configuration.

The context represents the current stickiness state. It knows whether we
are stuck to master for each of the different Makara configurations we
have defined. It's persisted between requests via an only cookie we set,
whose max age depends on stickiness duration for each of the
configurations we store at any given moment.

Rails 5.1 compat: coerce Relation arg to SQL string before matching against it

Makara hijacks `select_rows` and inspects the first argument, expecting
it to be a SQL string, to determine whether to route to primary or
replica connection.

In https://github.com/rails/rails/pull/25522 the method signature
changed to take an Arel relation instead of a SQL string, so all queries
will go to the primary database and none to the replica.

To fix, we'll need to either expect & duly inspect the Relation or call
`#to_sql` before checking. The first will take more code and possibly
introduce bugs; the second will mean a perf hit due to converting every
relation to SQL twice.
